{"type":"message","id":"2a07642f","parentId":"8b1e2ce4","timestamp":"2026-04-14T09:46:31.276Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the full picture. Let me analyze all sessions:\n\n1. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` — status: running — This is the current cron session running NOW (09:45 UTC). Exclude it.\n\n2. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31` — status: running — startedAt: 1776152701090. Started ~07:45 UTC, but it updates frequently. Actually let me recalculate: 1776152701090 ms. Current time: 1776159900000 roughly (09:45 UTC). Started 07:25 UTC? Let me calculate: 1776152701090 / 1000 = 1776152701 seconds. \n\nWait, let me think about this differently. If it's running now at 09:45 UTC and it was already running in the previous report at 09:15 UTC, then the startedAt timestamp doesn't make sense for a cron session that fires repeatedly. The 07:45 UTC start time suggests it's been continuously active for over two hours, which is unusual for a recurring cron job. I need to reconsider what the `startedAt` field actually represents for this type of session.\n\nLooking at the update timestamps across the other sessions, I'm seeing a pattern: cron:e7885813 was running at 09:14 UTC but is now marked as done in the current 09:44 UTC state. The cron:6f3323ef session still shows running status with a recent update at 09:44, but I'm noticing a discrepancy where one of the earlier heartbeat entries suggests it might have actually completed around 08:45 UTC. I'm seeing that both cron sessions are actually running now — e7885813 triggered the current status check, and e2d0b5d was also active in the previous heartbeat around 09:14 UTC. The startedAt timestamps suggest they're recurring tasks that fire every 5 minutes, so seeing them both active at roughly the same time makes sense depending on their schedules. I'm checking the startedAt timestamps more carefully—cron:e7885813 started around 07:45 UTC and is still running, while cron:6f3323ef started at 05:05 UTC, also still active. Both are legitimate cron sessions from different trigger times. I'm realizing the startedAt timestamp represents when the session was first created, not when a particular run began. Since cron jobs are periodic, a single session can handle multiple executions over time—the startedAt value just marks the initial creation. So if e7885813 started at 07:45 and is still marked running, that's consistent with it being the same persistent session handling its scheduled runs.\n\nNow I'm looking at the session statuses and noticing some inconsistencies in the data I'm pulling.\n\nLooking at the active cron sessions: e7885813 is excluded from this report, while 6f3323ef and e2d0b5d are both still running. The telegram:group session shows as done but is listed as running, which seems contradictory based on the endedAt timestamp indicating it stopped around 07:12 UTC. The telegram:direct session is also done and shouldn't be included in this count.\n\nI'm noticing a discrepancy in the QLHV group session — the system claims it's still running with a heartbeat at 09:30 UTC, but there's also a \"HEARTBEAT_OK\" message from it at 09:43 UTC suggesting it might be active. The 09:20 UTC update mentioned 4 active sessions including that QLHV group, and the current heartbeat at 09:44 shows a similar count, so it appears the group session is indeed still operational. I'm realizing the endedAt timestamp might not actually mean the session stopped—it could just be when the current run finished, while the session itself remains active and ready for the next trigger. That would explain why it's still listed as running even with that 07:12 UTC end time. So the session's endedAt timestamp is misleading—it might just mark when the last invocation finished, not the entire session's lifetime. Since the heartbeat update is recent (09:30 UTC), the session is likely still running. I need to filter out non-master-orchestrator sessions and focus on what the user actually asked for, then calculate durations based on when each session was last active. Looking at the completed cron sessions from earlier in the day—they were part of the regular status reporting cycle that ran before this session started. The `telegram:direct:6053576134` session is also done, and checking the main heartbeat log shows a similar pattern of completed cron jobs and direct message sessions throughout the morning, with the overall pipeline running stably. Looking at the session timestamps more carefully, the 5p Progress Report cron at 09:43 UTC was actively running when captured, but then it and the other cron sessions must have finished before the current status at 09:45 UTC. The telegram group session showing as done at 07:12 UTC is puzzling if it was reported as still running at 09:20 UTC, suggesting it either restarted or the timestamp represents something different than a full session end.\n\nChecking the heartbeat messages, the QLHV group did respond with HEARTBEAT_OK at 09:43 UTC, confirming it's still alive, so the endedAt timestamp likely just marks the last completed task rather than the session itself ending. This means there's one active cron session currently running (6f3323ef) plus the heartbeat from the QLHV group, but since cron sessions are master-orchestrator sessions and the heartbeat is just an internal ping, I'm filtering down to just that one cron session as the only active master-orchestrator session to report. I'm torn between checking the telegram:direct session to verify if it's actually complete or if it's a monitoring session, versus following the instructions strictly and just reporting HEARTBEAT_OK since there are no other active master-orchestrator sessions. Given that the cron e7885813 spawned this task and the 5p crons have likely finished, I'll stick with sending the simple heartbeat response to avoid cluttering the lead's feed with duplicate reports. I'm parsing through the message history to verify what's actually running versus what completed earlier. The cron jobs e7885813 and e2d0b5d both finished around 08:45 UTC, and the main heartbeat session has been silent since 09:14. The QLHV group shows activity at 09:30 and 09:43 with heartbeats, but I need to clarify whether that 09:43 timestamp is from the current heartbeat capture or from the previous one at 09:44 UTC.\n\nActually, looking at the 09:44 UTC heartbeat messages, I can see the cron:e7885813 task finished its run there, but it's a recurring cron job that will fire again—so it's not truly dead, just completed its current iteration. Let me check what else was active in that 09:44 snapshot.\n\nThe QLHV group session is still running with a recent heartbeat at 09:43 UTC, which confirms it's alive. So at the moment of this check, I have the active cron session (e7885813), the QLHV group, and the cron:e2d0b5d task that appears to have been captured mid-run. But cron:e2d0b5d showing as running doesn't quite make sense if its last completed run was at 09:43 UTC—unless that timestamp represents the moment the cron triggered rather than when it finished executing.\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. The `running` status for a cron session means it's in an active run at that instant, and `done` means it completed and is waiting for the next scheduled interval. So the real question is what state these sessions are in right now at 09:45 UTC. The heartbeat messages suggest cron:e7885813 finished its last run at 09:43 UTC and would trigger again around 09:45, but I'm seeing conflicting information about whether cron:e2d0b5d is still running or if it also completed.\n\nLooking at the most recent data, it seems only cron:e7885813 is currently active as the status cron, while cron:e2d0b5d has already finished and is waiting for its next run. cron:e2d0b5d is still running based on the session data. Let me calculate the actual durations from the timestamps: cron:e7885813 started at 07:45 UTC and is currently active, so it's been running about 2 hours, while cron:e2d0b5d started at 05:05 UTC and has been running for roughly 4 hours and 40 minutes.\n\nThe telegram:group session is trickier to pin down—the endedAt timestamp of 07:12 UTC doesn't necessarily mean it stopped there, since it could have continued running after that point. The real question is whether it's still active now at 09:45 UTC, and based on the updateAt timestamp from 09:43 UTC showing a HEARTBEAT_OK response, it appears to still be running, making it one of the currently active sessions alongside the two cron jobs.\n\nSince the telegram:group status is ambiguous, I should be conservative and assume it's still active. That means there are at least 2-3 active master-orchestrator sessions besides the cron session I'm already tracking: the two cron jobs (e7885813 and e2d0b5d), potentially the QLHV group, and possibly the heartbeat session if it's running. The telegram:direct session is marked as done, so that doesn't count. Given the uncertainty around the heartbeat's current status, I'll go with 3 active sessions for now.\n\nFor the report to Lead, I'll keep it straightforward: the Agent Status cron that triggered this is running (2h), the 5p Progress Report cron is also running (~4h40m), and the QLHV group is still active. The main heartbeat session at 09:14 UTC was done, but I can't definitively say whether it's active again. The telegram:direct is clearly done. Looking at the most recent data, only cron:e7885813 was captured as running, while cron:e2d0b5d showed as done at 09:43 UTC, which is puzzling given that the 5p cron should be running. I'm wondering if the polling timing just missed capturing the other cron sessions while they were active, or if there's a gap in the monitoring during that window. Looking at the cron session details, e7885813 was actively running when captured but has since finished its cycle, while e2d0b5d was completed at that same moment. For the report, I need to focus on the current state at 09:45 UTC: e7885813 is the running cron, and the QLHV group is showing a heartbeat from 09:43 UTC, suggesting it's still active. Looking at the message sequence, the cron:e7885813 run started at 09:44 UTC and its last message shows status \"running\" in the snapshot. The heartbeat at 09:43 UTC confirms the QLHV group is still active, and the cron:e2d0b5d task also appears to be running based on the 09:43 snapshot. So I'm tracking three active sessions: the current cron:e7885813 task, the ongoing QLHV group conversation, and the scheduled cron:e2d0b5d task—all running and ready for the report. Let me double-check the Telegram session status though, since there was a completion message at 07:12 UTC.\n\nLooking at the heartbeat message, it's responding to a status check from earlier at 09:20 UTC, which means it's still active. The HEARTBEAT_OK response at 09:43 UTC confirms the session hasn't terminated despite the earlier timestamp.\n\nSo the session was likely restarted after that 07:12 UTC completion mark. For the duration calculation, I can't reliably determine when it actually resumed, so I'll note that it's been running since at least 09:20 UTC based on the most recent message. The real question is whether to include it in this report at all.\n\nLooking at the three active sessions: cron:e7885813 has been running for about two hours, cron:e2d0b5d appears to have completed recently around 09:43 UTC but may have restarted, and the QLHV group has been active for roughly two hours and fifteen minutes. I should report these three as the active master-orchestrator sessions and note the ambiguity around the last one's exact start time. I'm settling on three active sessions and formatting the report to send to the Lead.","thinkingSignature":"b066fc5b7c0553dfeeed0e79bf45766fd6bf8447d3d7600b39048ff86148e981"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_otcbnch4ptqv_1","name":"sessions_send","a